    <!-- ========== Step 2: Connect your web GTM to sGTM ========== -->
    <div id="step-2" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg">2</div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Add an sGTM forwarding tag in your web GTM container</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="pl-14">
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
          You need the regular Google Tag Manager snippet on your website. <strong>If you already have GTM on your site, you're set</strong> —
          just follow the steps below to add the sGTM forwarding tag.
        </p>

        <!-- Platform tabs for installing GTM -->
        <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden group mb-4">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">
            <span class="font-medium text-gray-900 text-sm">Don't have GTM yet? Install it first</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-5 py-4 bg-gray-50 border-t border-gray-200 text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-3">
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800 mb-1">Webflow</h4>
              <p>Project Settings &rarr; Custom Code &rarr; paste in Head section</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800 mb-1">WordPress</h4>
              <p>Install the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/duracelltomi-google-tag-manager/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-indigo-600 underline">GTM4WP plugin</a> and enter your container ID</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800 mb-1">Squarespace</h4>
              <p>Settings &rarr; Developer Tools &rarr; Code Injection &rarr; paste in Header</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800 mb-1">Any other site</h4>
              <p>Paste the GTM snippet into your HTML <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">&lt;head&gt;</code> tag. <a href="https://support.google.com/tagmanager/answer/6103696" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-indigo-600 underline">Google's installation guide</a></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </details>

        <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-5 mb-6">
          <p class="text-green-800 font-medium mb-2">Key principle: your GA4 tag stays untouched</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-green-700 mb-3">
            mbuzz uses a <strong>dual-tag architecture</strong>. Your existing GA4 tag keeps sending data directly to Google
            as it always has. You add a <em>second</em> Google Tag that sends a parallel copy to your sGTM server for mbuzz.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-green-700">
            This means sGTM is <strong>never</strong> in the critical path for GA4. If your sGTM server goes down,
            GA4 keeps working. Only mbuzz data collection pauses until sGTM is back.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Create the sGTM forwarding tag</h4>
        <ol class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Open your <strong>web</strong> GTM container and go to <strong>Tags</strong> &rarr; <strong>New</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Choose <strong>Google Tag</strong> as the tag type</p>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">3</span>
            <div class="text-sm text-gray-700">
              <p>Set the <strong>Tag ID</strong> to your GA4 measurement ID (the same <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">G-XXXXXXXXXX</code> your existing GA4 tag uses)</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-1">The sGTM GA4 Client needs this measurement ID to parse the incoming request.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">4</span>
            <div class="text-sm text-gray-700">
              <p>Under <strong>Configuration settings</strong>, add a parameter:</p>
              <div class="mt-2 bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded p-3">
                <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 text-xs">
                  <div>
                    <div class="text-gray-500 mb-1">Configuration Parameter</div>
                    <div class="bg-white border border-gray-300 rounded px-2 py-1.5 font-mono">server_container_url</div>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <div class="text-gray-500 mb-1">Value</div>
                    <div class="bg-white border border-gray-300 rounded px-2 py-1.5 font-mono">https://sgtm.yoursite.com</div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2">Replace with your sGTM server URL from Step 1.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">5</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Set the trigger to <strong>All Pages</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">6</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Name it <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-sm">mbuzz - sGTM Forward</code> and click <strong>Save</strong></p>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <!-- What you should see -->
        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden mb-6">
          <img src="/images/docs/sgtm/sgtm-forward-tag.png" alt="Completed mbuzz - sGTM Forward tag in Google Tag Manager showing Google Tag type, server_container_url configuration parameter, and Initialization - All Pages trigger" class="w-full">
        </div>

        <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm text-amber-800 mb-4">
          <strong>Do NOT modify your existing GA4 tag.</strong> Your original Google Tag (the one without
          <code class="bg-amber-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">server_container_url</code>) must keep sending to GA4 directly.
          The new tag runs alongside it — same triggers, same measurement ID, but routing to sGTM instead.
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm text-gray-600">
          <strong>What you should have after this step:</strong> Two Google Tags in your web GTM container —
          your original GA4 tag sending directly to Google, and a new
          <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">mbuzz - sGTM Forward</code> tag sending to your sGTM server.
          Both fire on All Pages.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ========== Step 3: Add the mbuzz tag ========== -->
    <div id="step-3" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg">3</div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Add the mbuzz tag to your sGTM container</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="pl-14">
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
          This is where mbuzz gets connected. You'll import our tag template, then create one tag per call type.
          mbuzz uses a <strong>4-call model</strong>: Session, Event, Conversion, and Identify. Each tag is a separate
          instance of the same template with different settings.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-lg divide-y divide-gray-200">

          <!-- ===== Sub-step 3a: Import the template ===== -->
          <div class="p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-7 h-7 bg-green-100 text-green-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">a</span>
              <div class="flex-1">
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Import the mbuzz tag template</h4>
                <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-1.5">
                  <li>Open your <strong>server-side</strong> GTM container (not the client-side one)</li>
                  <li>Click <strong>Templates</strong> in the left sidebar</li>
                  <li>Under Tag Templates, click <strong>Search Gallery</strong></li>
                  <li>Search for <strong>"mbuzz"</strong></li>
                  <li>Click <strong>Add to workspace</strong>, then <strong>Add</strong></li>
                </ol>
                <div class="mt-3 bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded p-3 text-xs text-gray-500">
                  <strong>Manual import:</strong> Download from
                  <a href="https://github.com/mbuzzco/mbuzz-sgtm" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-indigo-600 underline">github.com/mbuzzco/mbuzz-sgtm</a>.
                  In GTM: Templates &rarr; New &rarr; Import &rarr; select the <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">template.tpl</code> file.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- ===== Sub-step 3b: Session tag ===== -->
          <div class="p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-7 h-7 bg-green-100 text-green-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">b</span>
              <div class="flex-1">
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Create the Session tag</h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-3">
                  Fires on <strong>every page view</strong>. Creates visitors and sessions with full attribution (UTM params, referrer, channel).
                  This is the foundation — all other tags depend on it.
                </p>

                <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-1.5 mb-4">
                  <li>Go to <strong>Tags</strong> &rarr; <strong>New</strong></li>
                  <li>Name it: <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs">mbuzz - Session</code></li>
                  <li>Tag type: <strong>mbuzz — Server-Side Attribution</strong></li>
                  <li>Fill in the fields:</li>
                </ol>

                <!-- Tag config visual -->
                <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 mb-4">
                  <div class="text-xs font-semibold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">Tag Configuration</div>
                  <div class="space-y-3">
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3">
                      <div>
                        <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">API Key <span class="text-red-400">*</span></div>
                        <div class="bg-white border border-gray-300 rounded px-3 py-2 text-sm text-gray-700 font-mono">sk_live_your_key_here</div>
                      </div>
                      <div>
                        <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">Call Type <span class="text-red-400">*</span></div>
                        <div class="bg-white border border-gray-300 rounded px-3 py-2 text-sm text-gray-700">Session</div>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="text-xs text-gray-400 italic">No other fields needed for Session tags. URL, referrer, and UTM params are captured automatically.</div>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <ol start="5" class="list-decimal list-inside text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-1.5 mb-3">
                  <li>Set the <strong>Trigger</strong> to <strong>All Pages</strong> (the default Page View trigger)</li>
                  <li>Click <strong>Save</strong></li>
                </ol>

                <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded p-3 text-xs text-green-700">
                  <strong>What this does:</strong> On every page view, the tag reads (or creates) a visitor ID cookie,
                  computes a device fingerprint, and calls <code class="bg-green-100 px-1 rounded">POST /api/v1/sessions</code>.
                  mbuzz extracts UTM params from the URL, classifies the traffic channel, and creates or continues a session.
